To declare a template class as inline, you simply need to add the `inline` keyword before the template keyword:

```c++
inline template<class T>
class MyTemplateClass {
    // ...
};
```

This tells the compiler to generate the template code in every translation unit that uses it, rather than just generating it in one place and letting the linker handle it. This ensures that the constructor for the template class is always called, regardless of how the template is used in the code.

If you're getting the error "inline specifier is ignored when there are no declarators", it means that you're trying to apply the `inline` keyword to the template class itself, without actually declaring any instances of the class.

To use the `inline` keyword with a template class, you need to use it in conjunction with an actual declaration of the class, such as when you declare an instance of the class:

```c++
template<class T>
class MyTemplateClass {
    // ...
};

inline MyTemplateClass<int> myInstance;
```

This would declare an instance of the `MyTemplateClass` template with `int` as the template parameter, and declare it as `inline`. When you use this declaration in your code, the constructor for `MyTemplateClass` will be called automatically, since it's an instance of the class.

If you have a source code file (a .cpp file) that you want to make sure gets compiled and linked into the final binary, regardless of whether it's explicitly used or not, you can use a technique called "force linking".

To force a specific source file to be linked into the executable, you can define a dummy variable in that file, and then reference that variable from another source file in the same project. This will force the linker to include the source file in the final binary, even if no other code in the file is actually used.

Here's an example:

First, in your source code file that you want to force link (let's call it "my_module_a.cpp"), define a dummy variable like this:

```c++
int my_dummy_variable_for_my_module_a_cpp = 0;
```

This will create a variable called "my_dummy_variable_for_my_module_a_cpp", which will be initialized to 0 when the program starts.

Next, in some other source code file (let's call it "main.cpp"), reference the dummy variable like this:

```c++
extern int my_dummy_variable_for_my_module_a_cpp;

int main() {
    // do some stuff...
    return my_dummy_variable_for_my_module_a_cpp;
}
```

This will cause the linker to include "my_module_a.cpp" in the final binary, since it's referenced from "main.cpp".

Note that this technique should be used sparingly, since it can increase the size of the final binary unnecessarily. Only use it for files that you know need to be included, but which may not be used explicitly.

Yes, there are better ways to accomplish this than using a global variable. Here are a few alternative techniques:

1. Use a static function: Define a static function in the source file that you want to force link, and then call that function from another source file in the same project. The function could simply return a value, or perform some other action that you don't care about. The key is to make sure the function is not optimized away by the compiler.

```c++
// In my_module_a.cpp:
static void force_link() {
    // Do nothing...
}

// In main.cpp:
extern void force_link();

int main() {
    // Call the function to force linking...
    force_link();

    return 0;
}
```

2. Use a linker script: A linker script is a file that specifies how object files should be linked together to form an executable. You could create a linker script that explicitly includes the source files you want to force link, regardless of whether they're used or not. Here's an example:

```ld
GROUP(
    my_module_a.o
    my_module_b.o
)

INPUT(-lc -lm)
```

This linker script defines a "GROUP" of object files that should always be included in the final executable, regardless of whether they're used or not. You would then pass this linker script to the linker when building your executable.

3. Use compiler-specific options: Some compilers provide options that let you force specific object files to be linked. For example, with GCC you can use the "-Wl,--whole-archive" linker option to force all objects in a given library or object file to be included in the final executable, regardless of whether they're used or not. Here's an example:

```sh
g++ -o my_program main.cpp -Wl,--whole-archive my_module_a.o my_module_b.o -Wl,--no-whole-archive
```

This command will link the "my_program" executable, including all objects in "my_module_a.o" and "my_module_b.o".

Note that all of these techniques have some drawbacks and should be used with care. In general, it's a good idea to write your code in a way that ensures all source files are used as intended, so you don't have to resort to these techniques.
